{"parse":{"title":"Weathering hypothesis","pageid":57165508,"revid":858612752,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>weathering hypothesis</b> was first proposed by <a href=\"/wiki/Arline_Geronimus\" title=\"Arline Geronimus\">Arline Geronimus</a> in 1992. It holds that <a href=\"/wiki/African-American_women\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"African-American women\">African American women's</a> health deteriorates in early adulthood as a result of their cumulative exposure to socioeconomic disadvantage.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Subsequent studies by her and others have found support for the hypothesis.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> In recent years, the hypothesis has been examined with regard to phenomena such as <a href=\"/wiki/Allostatic_load\" title=\"Allostatic load\">allostatic load</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Epigenetics\" title=\"Epigenetics\">epigenetics</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Telomere\" title=\"Telomere\">telomere</a> shortening.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Origin\">Origin</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Weathering_hypothesis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Origin\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>While working part-time at a school for pregnant teenagers in <a href=\"/wiki/Trenton,_New_Jersey\" title=\"Trenton, New Jersey\">Trenton, New Jersey</a>, Geronimus first noticed that the teens who came to the school tended to have far more health problems than her classmates at <a href=\"/wiki/Princeton_University\" title=\"Princeton University\">Princeton University</a>. She thus began to wonder whether the health conditions of the teens at that clinic may have been caused by their environment. While in graduate school, she proposed the \"weathering hypothesis\". She chose the term <a href=\"/wiki/Weathering\" title=\"Weathering\">weathering</a> as a metaphor for the effects she perceived that exposure to stress was having on the health of marginalized people.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Weathering_hypothesis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Race_and_health_in_the_United_States#African-Americans\" title=\"Race and health in the United States\">Race and health in the United States#African-Americans</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Weathering_hypothesis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Geronimus, A. T. (1992). \"The weathering hypothesis and the health of African-American women and infants: evidence and speculations\". <i>Ethnicity &amp; Disease</i>. <b>2</b> (3): 207\u2013221. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Serial_Number\" title=\"International Standard Serial Number\">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/issn/1049-510X\">1049-510X</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Identifier\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"PubMed Identifier\">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1467758\">1467758</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Ethnicity+%26+Disease&amp;rft.atitle=The+weathering+hypothesis+and+the+health+of+African-American+women+and+infants%3A+evidence+and+speculations&amp;rft.volume=2&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=207-221&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F1467758&amp;rft.issn=1049-510X&amp;rft.aulast=Geronimus&amp;rft.aufirst=A.+T.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AWeathering+hypothesis\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Geronimus, Arline T. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/027795369500159X\">\"Black/white differences in the relationship of maternal age to birthweight: A population-based test of the weathering hypothesis\"</a>. <i>Social Science &amp; Medicine</i>. <b>42</b> (4): 589\u2013597. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1016/0277-9536%2895%2900159-x\">10.1016/0277-9536(95)00159-x</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Social+Science+%26+Medicine&amp;rft.atitle=Black%2Fwhite+differences+in+the+relationship+of+maternal+age+to+birthweight%3A+A+population-based+test+of+the+weathering+hypothesis&amp;rft.volume=42&amp;rft.issue=4&amp;rft.pages=589-597&a